# Agent Safety And Commit Workflow

- Do not delete files, folders, or git-tracked content unless the user gives clear, explicit authorization in the current conversation.
- If cleanup is needed, prefer reorganizing, moving, renaming, or archiving items instead of deleting them.
- If there is any ambiguity about whether an action is destructive, treat it as destructive and ask first.
- Prefer reversible changes during cleanup and refactoring.
- Before any hard-to-reverse operation, pause and confirm with the user.
- Do not rewrite git history, prune git objects, run aggressive garbage collection, or perform any recovery-impacting git operation unless the user explicitly authorizes that specific action in the current conversation.
- Before any history rewrite or destructive git cleanup, create a verified backup outside the repository and confirm that the backup exists before proceeding.
- After any backup step, verify the backup path immediately and report it back before continuing.
- If local-only files were intentionally kept outside git, do not touch or replace them unless the user explicitly asks.

- At the end of every task, explicitly ask whether the user wants a git commit.
- Do not create a commit unless the user clearly approves it in the current conversation.
- If the user approves a commit, write a detailed commit message that explains why the change was made and the main scope of the changes.

- When reorganizing manuscript or project files, preserve legacy materials unless the user explicitly authorizes removal.
- When handling feedback-driven revisions, keep review artifacts, comment summaries, and revision-history records separate and traceable.
